title: For Sale:   Russian SKS and Rifle
postcontent:
The SKS is a Russian semi-automatic carbine, designed in 1945 by Sergei Gavrilovich Simonov. It is formally known as the Samozaryadnyi Karabin sistemi Simonova, 1945 (Self-loading Carbine, Simonov's system, 1945), or SKS 45. It was originally planned to serve as the new standard issue weapon for the Soviet military forces, alongside Mikhail Kalashnikov' new AK-47 design to replace the Mosin-Nagant series of bolt-action rifles and carbines that had been in service since 1891. As mass production of AK-pattern rifles increased, the SKS carbine was soon phased out of service. The carbine was quickly replaced by the AK-47, but it remained in second-line service for decades afterwards, and remains a ceremonial arm today. It was widely exported and produced by the former Eastern Bloc nations, as well as China. It is today popular on the civilian surplus market in many countries.

The carbine was chambered for the then-new 7.62 x 39 mm M1943 round, an intermediate cartridge which went on to become a standard for the subsequent AK-pattern rifles. 


The Rifle is a 1945 Mosin-Nagant M44


I'm asking 500 for the Sks and 200 obo for the rifle I'll cut you a deal if you purchase as a set Text me with any questions open to reasonable offers 1-REDACTED

title: For Sale/Trade:  Spanish .38 Largo Black Powder Revolver
postcontent: For sale or trade is a Spanish .38 Largo black powder revolver.  The .38 Largo is also known as the .38 Long and the .38 Long Colt.  This gun will chamber the .38 Special and .38 Short rounds, but it is not safe to fire a modern smokeless powder .38 Special or .38 Short cartridge in this gun.  It can cock and the cylinder revolves, but may not line up with the barrel.  It was made in the 1910 to 1931 timeframe in the Eibar area of Spain, and these guns were typically low quality guns.  It is a near perfect copy of the Smith and Wesson Military and Police Model.  It’s an inexpensive made, low quality revolver, intended for low pressure black powder loads, not modern day smokeless powder loads.  I bought it as a tinkering project about a year ago, and after removing some crud on the barrel, discovered it was a black powder gun, and have not fooled with it since. Since it’s a near perfect copy of the S&W M&P Model, I’m selling it as a good conversation piece and as an antiquity, and the purchaser must agree to not fire it.  Local sale only – I won’t ship.  I prefer a cash sale, but would be interested in an even trade for a project gun that needs repair.  I would prefer a pistol of any caliber, but would be open to a .22 rifle or a shotgun, but no black powder guns.  I will meet with you within a 15 mile radius of the Mobile, AL airport for the sale or trade, during daylight hours only.  $50 or BEST OFFER or TRADE.  If you don't like the price, make me an offer - I'm trying to clean out and you never know - I might take it.  E-mail me with any questions – I don’t do texts.  If the ad is still up, it's still available.

The PX4 Storm SD .45 ACP semiauto pistol was developed to meet the very demanding requirements issued by the US Special Forces Command (SOCOM) for their Joint Combat Pistol. They called for superior weather resistance, three magazines (one 9-round flush and two 10-round extended), dark earth frame, extended barrel for threading, tactical case and additional accessories. Beretta answered the call successfuly, not just by merely rechambering the PX4 Storm to .45 ACP--but rather by redesigning its internal components to meet and exceed all these requirements. The result is a pistol that satisfies not only SOCOM's requirements, but the most demanding shooter looking for the absolute best and most reliable for personal defense, competition or carry.
Special Duty (SD) Tactical Pistol
The “SD” denomination of this handgun stands for “Special Duty.” That means a pistol that will be reliable in the toughest and most demanding conditions. Military trials for the PX4 Storm SD have proven that it will keep performing in spite of salt, mud, water, rain, snow, sand or anything else you can throw at it. This is because every internal component was engineered, produced and treated to function in such extreme environments.
Low-Recoil, Powerful Super-Accurate
The PX4 Storm SD features a rotating barrel system. This means that under recoil, the barrel rotates, thereby dissipating momentum radially, which translates in much lower felt recoil and muzzle jump, even with hotter .45 ACP rounds. Furthermore, the extended cold-hammer forged barrel is 4.5” long and allows the power of the .45 to fully develop before exiting the muzzle. And the out-of-the-box accuracy of this handgun is as good as it gets in a tactical pistol.
Packed with Tactical Features The reversible mag-release, ambidextrous safety, drop-free magazine, commander-style hammer and easy-on-target 3-dot sights are only some of the tactical features of this Beretta .45. An integral Picatinny rail forward of the trigger guard enables easy mounting of tactical lights, laser aiming devices or other accessories. And like all best-quality military arms the PX4 Storm SD takes mere seconds to disassemble without any tools. When the impossible is expected, the PX4 Storm SD is the absolute best companion to have at hand.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Astra 900 Broomhandle Pistol and ammo.
postcontent:
For sale is an Astra 900 broomhandle pistol. Inspired by the Mauser C96 this weapon was produced in Spain under license from Mauser sometime in the early 1940s. I am including a box and a half of ammo and the spent casings if you're a reloader. Be aware this gun uses 7.63x25, that's 7.6[THREE]x25, NOT 7.62x25 Tokarev. The Tokarev ammunition is way too high-pressure for broomhandles and will blow them up. 

This particular 900 is in refurbished condition. The stock has been lost and the bore is dark and worn. However, it's not as bad as it sounds! The benefit of a refurbished gun over a collector's item is that you can shoot it guilt-free! Turning heads at the range is a blast with this gun and you wont have to worry about damaging a showpiece. The serials on this gun all match, even those below the grips, the crown is crisp, and a because it was re-blued the finish is impeccable. The action, slide, and safety all work properly and all in all this is a great gun for people whose collections don't have room for space-wasting safe queens who are afraid to be shot once in a while.
